The input string seems to present a pre-order traversal of the tree.

So an algorithm would typically use recursion or a stack to unwind that string into an actual node-based tree structure.

Here is some code:


``` 
import java.util.*; 

class Node {
    char val;
    Node left = null;
    Node right = null;

    Node(char val) {
        this.val = val;
    }

    static Node fromString(String str) {
        Stack&lt;Node&gt; stack = new Stack&lt;Node&gt;();
        Node node = new Node(&#39; &#39;);
        Node stub = node;
        boolean goRight = false;
        
        for (int i = 0, n = str.length() ; i &lt; n ; i++) { 
            char c = str.charAt(i); 
            if (c == &#39;x&#39;) {
                if (goRight) {
                    node.right = null;
                    node = stack.pop();
                } else {
                    node.left = null;
                    goRight = true;
                }
            } else {
                Node child = new Node(c);
                if (goRight) {
                    node.right = child;
                    node = node.right;
                    goRight = false;
                } else {
                    node.left = child;
                    stack.push(node);
                    node = node.left;
                }
            }
        }
        return stub.left;
    }
}
```

You can call it like this:

    Node root = Node.fromString(&quot;AAAxxxAxx&quot;);

